1.body:
A compiler is a software tool used to convert a high level language into a low level machine language which can be executed on a computer. Often when somone is talking about compilation or a compiled programming language they are refering to a language like C/C++/Rust but languages like Python, Javascript are also compiled into a low level bytecode representation which can then be executed on an interpreter (a virtual machine) like CPython, V8, JVM. A simple hello world program written in C #include <stdio.h> int main() { printf("hello world"); } and compile as $gcc -S main.c and you will get the compiled assembly representation of your hello world program. .file	"main.c" .text .section	.rodata

main:

10.body: In this book we will go through some opensource commercial compilers that are used in the software industry today. Among them will be GCC , LLVM , MLIR . LLVM is the main focus of this book since it's language agnostic and provides advanced optimization and analysis. Beside LLVM we will also look into compiler implementation of functional programming languages.
10.title: Compilers in practice

11.body: This book is heavy on practical implementation rather than theoratical consideration. For that there are lots of other books. There is a lot to writing a compiler from frontend to the backend. Writing a compiler is not too hard but writing an optimizing compiler is a difficult task. There are already a lot of resource material on writing basic compilers like, Crafting interpreters

12.body: List of general compiler books Compilers: Principals, Techniques and Tools by Alfred V. Aho et. al. This book is called the "dragon book" and is one of the most famous compiler book out there. I have seen people argue how relevent it is in modern times. Modern compiler implementation in ML by Adrew W. Appel This is a really good book on practical compiler construction in ML functional programming language. There are C and Java versions too but ML would be a better alternative to them for compiler construction. Engineering A compiler by Keith D. Cooper A modern compiler book but lots on theory. A better alternative to the Dragon book. Modern Compiler Design by Dick Grune A modern alternative to the dragon book. Advanced books on optimizing compiler construction Advanced Compiler Design and Implementation by Steven Muchnick An extensive resource on algorithms used in modern optimizing compilers. A really good book for understanding industrial stregth optimizing compilers. High Performance compilers for Parallel computing by Michael Wolf The book by Steven Muchnick mostly focuses on optimizing programs for uniprocessor computers. This book fills the gap and provides a comprehensive introduction to transformation and analysis for parallel computing.
12.title: Books on compilers

2.body: Compilers were developed to improve how we represent computation (algorithms) and to decrease software (software was not a term back in the 1940s and 50s) complexity. Assembly language was actually developed as a high level language over binary representation used in the earlier systems. In today's standards writing assembly language is considered bad since compilers are better than the programmer (which is what we will see in this book) at generating fast and correct code. Although there are some niche instances where the programmer with assembly is better than the compiler itself, mostly in very low level programming and in computational kernel development (BLAS type stuff). Compilers are the most studied area of computer science and the parsing methods used in compiler construction is the most well established area in theoratical computer science. These days most effort is put into the backend of the compiler (the transformation and analysis phases). Compilers are also very complex tools. I would compilers to be the most complex software out there.
2.title: Why is compiler important ?
